Poland international and former Arsenal goalkeeper Wojciech Szczesny has insisted he will refuse to play in next month’s World Cup qualifier against Russia following Vladimir Putin's invasion of Ukraine. Szczesny has a Ukrainian wife and has sensationally revealed he will not play against players who "represent the values and principles of Russia". On Wednesday, Russian president Putin ordered an invasion of eastern Ukraine as European tensions escalated. Captain Robert Lewandowski was the first Poland player to speak out about the stance, tweeting that it was the "right decision". “The moment Putin decided to invade Ukraine he declared war not only on Ukraine but also on all the values Europe stands for. Liberty, Independence but most of all Peace. “I refuse to stand on the pitch, wearing the colours of my country and listen to the national anthem of Russia!